1
00:00:01,094 --> 00:00:29,868
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samasambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samasambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samasambuddhasa

2
00:00:31,385 --> 00:00:36,189
Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble and Fully Self-Enlightened One.

3
00:00:39,314 --> 00:00:45,780
We've now discussed two of the three characteristics that the Buddha taught to be the fundamental marks of all existence.

4
00:00:47,182 --> 00:00:53,950
The first, dukkha, unsatisfactoriness, pertains to any sentient being and especially human beings.

5
00:00:54,942 --> 00:01:03,298
how they contact and make sense of the world, and how a delusive relationship to sensual pain and pleasure causes suffering.

6
00:01:04,579 --> 00:01:10,490
We manufacture our own suffering because we believe that happiness is to be found in the sensual world.

7
00:01:13,135 --> 00:01:18,486
Then there was the quality of anicca, transience, the fact that everything is in process.

8
00:01:19,731 --> 00:01:25,278
As we also know from our science, there isn't actually any thing as such in the universe.

9
00:01:26,019 --> 00:01:29,804
It's all energy changing from one shape or form into another.

10
00:01:29,843 --> 00:01:35,411
Both of these two characteristics aren't difficult to grasp.

11
00:01:35,430 --> 00:01:44,102
The only small difficulty I think we have is to see how indulgence in pleasure always brings dissatisfaction in its wake.

12
00:01:45,635 --> 00:01:54,382
The third characteristic, however, anatta, or the doctrine of not-self, as it can be translated literally, is more difficult for us to grasp.

13
00:01:55,343 --> 00:02:09,257
But nonetheless, we can begin to intellectually understand the Buddha's position that nothing in the universe has substance, and the self, this person, that I feel and experience myself to be, is but a phantasm.

14
00:02:10,377 --> 00:02:15,102
It doesn't really have any real, substantial, essential existence.

15
00:02:17,021 --> 00:02:20,006
First of all, we need to see the Buddha was not a philosopher.

16
00:02:21,067 --> 00:02:32,662
He was not a philosopher if what we mean by that word is someone who is concerned to convince someone else of an idea, someone who is simply concerned to prove a given premise.

17
00:02:34,063 --> 00:02:39,350
For the philosopher, it is satisfying enough to have someone agree with them.

18
00:02:39,466 --> 00:02:47,754
For instance, if a philosopher states that happiness is the goal of life, their concern is to prove that premise by various arguments.

19
00:02:48,915 --> 00:02:54,001
It matters little whether the philosopher themselves actually lives a happy life or not.

20
00:02:54,641 --> 00:03:02,710
It's an ideal, an idea worth striving for, even if the philosopher at heart doesn't really know whether it's possible or not.

21
00:03:03,770 --> 00:03:07,735
What is necessary is that they are convinced by reasonable argument.

22
00:03:08,473 --> 00:03:10,915
but in this sense we're all philosophers to a degree.

23
00:03:12,016 --> 00:03:13,598
We prefer enticing logic.

24
00:03:14,379 --> 00:03:20,445
There's a part of us that feels satisfied that we've understood, accepted, and have faith in a statement.

25
00:03:21,567 --> 00:03:28,813
Believing in something is so much easier than coming to know by one's own personal experience.

26
00:03:28,834 --> 00:03:32,837
That's what we mean by realization, making it real for ourselves.

27
00:03:33,818 --> 00:03:36,320
But this demands effort, a lot of effort.

28
00:03:38,191 --> 00:03:41,956
The Buddha was well acquainted with all the philosophical viewpoints of his day.

29
00:03:43,239 --> 00:03:49,808
As the discussions he has with various Brahmins and wandering ascetics show, he was able to do more than hold his own.

30
00:03:50,789 --> 00:03:52,231
But he knew where arguments stopped.

31
00:03:53,074 --> 00:03:59,062
What he saw was that these Brahmins and Samana were caught up in simply trying to win arguments.

32
00:04:00,024 --> 00:04:03,810
They were, he said, ensnared in a jungle of views and opinions.

33
00:04:05,409 --> 00:04:08,215
The Buddha had no reason to win arguments for winning's sake.

34
00:04:09,116 --> 00:04:19,173
His aim was not simply to convince people that his understanding was correct, but, and here's the difference, he wanted people to experience what he had experienced.

35
00:04:20,416 --> 00:04:29,072
In this sense he was a mystic, not some new age spaced out psychic you understand, but someone who has understood the deeper mysteries of life.

36
00:04:29,524 --> 00:04:40,122
someone who has realized, actually experienced for themselves, something beyond the world of apparition, the world of things, the world of sense-data and thought, beyond the phenomenal world.

37
00:04:41,584 --> 00:04:52,983
The Buddha referred to himself as the Tathagata, which translated literally means thus gone, or perhaps arrived there, but it was his way of saying transcendent.

38
00:04:54,213 --> 00:04:58,779
The Buddha's concern was to get people to have the same supramundane experience.

39
00:04:59,682 --> 00:05:09,778
Hence everything he said had the purpose of getting those convinced to do the practice, to work at the practice in order to experience what he himself had attained.

40
00:05:11,019 --> 00:05:20,574
Unlike the philosopher, he really did know that happiness was the goal of human endeavor because he himself lived in perfect contentment and peace.

41
00:05:22,951 --> 00:05:26,836
So now we come to this difficult teaching of anatta, not self.

42
00:05:28,177 --> 00:05:33,725
The primary confusion is that this is one of those philosophical premises that we can argue about.

43
00:05:34,827 --> 00:05:40,656
That anatta means there is no self, no soul, no eternal spirit, and so on.

44
00:05:41,057 --> 00:05:42,379
This is quite understandable.

45
00:05:43,221 --> 00:05:53,574
Even people in his own day accused the Buddha of being an annihilationist, that is, someone who didn't believe in an eternal self and that the human simply vanished in total at death.

46
00:05:54,855 --> 00:06:04,427
There was no afterlife, and even if there were, as some annihilationists believed, in the end it would just fizzle out when karma had completed its momentum.

47
00:06:05,949 --> 00:06:09,072
But the Buddha insisted he was not an annihilationist.

48
00:06:09,711 --> 00:06:13,497
and that the only annihilation was of greed, hatred and delusion.

49
00:06:15,120 --> 00:06:20,228
The Buddha's position was grounded in his present state, which he referred to as nibbana.

50
00:06:21,509 --> 00:06:26,276
Everything was to be measured against that living experience.

51
00:06:26,297 --> 00:06:34,470
Perhaps he would have been on easier ground if he had used an expression as not-nibbana for everything that the unenlightened person experienced.

52
00:06:35,699 --> 00:06:46,151
In fact, there is a discourse where greater and greater pleasures are described, beginning with the delicious sensual pleasures and rising to the highest bliss of jhanic absorption.

53
00:06:47,192 --> 00:06:52,038
And he says that all these states are not the highest happiness, that is, not Nibbana.

54
00:06:54,281 --> 00:07:02,009
Although the Buddha's choice of the word anatta did and still confuses, he had good reason for choosing this word instead of others.

55
00:07:03,086 --> 00:07:17,785
He wanted to undermine the belief that anything a person experienced, whether through the five senses or the mind with its thoughts and images, or the heart with all its emotions and moods, in any way constituted something solid or everlasting.

56
00:07:19,728 --> 00:07:26,495
To do this he would deconstruct the human being, and he did this by looking at the human being in various ways.

57
00:07:28,399 --> 00:07:34,786
We shall look at three of them, by where the aggregates, the spheres, and the four foundations of mindfulness.

58
00:07:36,408 --> 00:07:46,737
By this process of deconstruction, the idea of something, anything, being whole, entire unto itself, an integer, a one, is undermined.

59
00:07:48,319 --> 00:07:58,288
It is natural for the discriminative mind to see things as individual objects, to see objects as isolated, to cut up the world into this and that.

60
00:07:58,555 --> 00:07:59,795
and it's necessary we do so.

61
00:08:00,918 --> 00:08:04,822
Can you imagine not being able to tell the difference between a cup of tea and a cup of water?

62
00:08:05,603 --> 00:08:06,144
Heaven forbid.

63
00:08:06,184 --> 00:08:13,432
There's nothing wrong with seeing the world like this so long as we also see it isn't the way things really are.

64
00:08:14,874 --> 00:08:19,459
This ability of the mind to create concepts is not destroyed by enlightenment.

65
00:08:20,141 --> 00:08:22,182
It is simply put in its proper context.

66
00:08:23,310 --> 00:08:24,973
There's a good example of this in art.

67
00:08:25,935 --> 00:08:29,521
Artists are forever trying to show us how the world really is.

68
00:08:29,541 --> 00:08:35,952
The Impressionists made us see that objects can only be fully understood within the environment they stand.

69
00:08:37,134 --> 00:08:39,317
A tree colours into the countryside.

70
00:08:40,921 --> 00:08:44,307
The Expressionists showed us that what we see is coloured by our emotions.

71
00:08:45,873 --> 00:08:46,855
Now let's take a car.

72
00:08:47,657 --> 00:08:48,337
That's an object.

73
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:51,885
We see it quite distinctly as separate from its environment.

74
00:08:52,847 --> 00:08:57,418
We see it moving as a separate object, and we know if we get in the way it's going to hurt.

75
00:08:58,681 --> 00:09:06,177
At an ordinary, conventional level of understanding, a car is hard and solid and is one thing, but we know it's made up.

76
00:09:07,355 --> 00:09:12,440
If we laid out all the pieces of a car on the floor, we wouldn't say that's a car.

77
00:09:13,461 --> 00:09:15,923
We'd say they're all the parts necessary to make up a car.

78
00:09:16,724 --> 00:09:20,388
Then, when we put it together, something quite magical happens.

79
00:09:21,149 --> 00:09:22,210
It propels itself.

80
00:09:23,130 --> 00:09:25,113
Definitely more amazing is an aeroplane.

81
00:09:25,753 --> 00:09:30,618
Tons of metal and what have you just lift so easily, so gracefully into flight.

82
00:09:32,419 --> 00:09:37,345
And what we come to realise is the whole is always greater than the sum of the parts.

83
00:09:37,847 --> 00:09:39,090
even at a basic level.

84
00:09:39,691 --> 00:09:45,200
Take a few bits of wood and put them together, and hey presto, a chair, a table, a bed, and so on.

85
00:09:47,202 --> 00:09:55,697
When we look at the universe, we see it as a collection of holes, forming greater holes, until we arrive at the hole which is the cosmos itself.

86
00:09:57,779 --> 00:09:59,503
When we look at a human being, it's the same.

87
00:10:00,443 --> 00:10:03,349
If you're a materialist for whom only matter exists,

88
00:10:03,869 --> 00:10:05,410
Then there's the wonder of consciousness.

89
00:10:06,130 --> 00:10:18,302
When all the bits and pieces are put together and functioning, there arises this mysterious capacity to be conscious, to be aware, and in higher primates and human beings to be self-aware.

90
00:10:20,004 --> 00:10:24,950
This is something extra that arises inexplicably, accidentally, incidentally.

91
00:10:26,291 --> 00:10:29,394
This by-product is called by philosophers an epiphenomena.

92
00:10:30,315 --> 00:10:32,576
Once we label something, we think we understand it.

93
00:10:33,687 --> 00:10:36,009
Now it's this very by-product that confuses us.

94
00:10:36,831 --> 00:10:41,196
Something that's made up of lots of other things produces a new function.

95
00:10:42,197 --> 00:10:45,782
The car made up of bits propels itself, the plane flies.

96
00:10:46,643 --> 00:10:49,105
And we see it as a whole, an integer, a one.

97
00:10:50,048 --> 00:10:51,669
We forget it's made up of parts.

98
00:10:52,931 --> 00:10:58,378
It's only when the car won't start, or the plane drops out of the sky, that we're suddenly pulled up short.

99
00:10:59,505 --> 00:11:06,056
It's only when a part of the body hurts or becomes ill that we suddenly realize that holes are made up of parts.

100
00:11:08,820 --> 00:11:15,328
Now the most common deconstruction device in the discourses is the aggregates or collections or heaps, the candor.

101
00:11:16,671 --> 00:11:19,455
You will notice here links with the dependent originations.

102
00:11:21,022 --> 00:11:32,059
The Buddha divides the human into five different aggregates, the physical base, perceptions, feelings, volitional formations and cognition.

103
00:11:33,923 --> 00:11:47,586
The physical base or rupa is again divided into four primary elements we've mentioned before, earth or solidity, fire or temperature, air or movement and water or cohesion.

104
00:11:49,490 --> 00:11:53,676
These four great elements are the way that the mind first experiences matter.

105
00:11:54,876 --> 00:12:00,644
At that basic percept there is only the object, the sense faculty, and cognition, a knowing.

106
00:12:02,106 --> 00:12:06,873
Sound, for instance, at this level, is experienced simply as pressure on the eardrum.

107
00:12:07,793 --> 00:12:09,917
Heaviness or lightness, that's the earth element.

108
00:12:11,339 --> 00:12:13,140
It's not that the other elements are not present.

109
00:12:14,222 --> 00:12:17,386
All the elements are present in any one given percept.

110
00:12:17,705 --> 00:12:19,086
but one always predominates.

111
00:12:20,269 --> 00:12:22,731
Fire or temperature would predominate in sight.

112
00:12:23,994 --> 00:12:26,177
Where there's light, there's heat, and vice versa.

113
00:12:27,558 --> 00:12:32,647
So the whole experience of sense contact can be deconstructed into these elements.

114
00:12:34,970 --> 00:12:42,902
Now whether these elements actually exist outside the mind is not relevant, for these are simply the way the senses sense the world out there.

115
00:12:44,636 --> 00:12:51,764
And in our meditation, we can do it in a more obvious way by experiencing the different parts of the body from this point of view.

116
00:12:53,004 --> 00:12:56,469
Bones can be felt as solid, just the quality of hardness.

117
00:12:58,190 --> 00:13:01,493
The heat or cold we feel can be seen as just temperature.

118
00:13:03,975 --> 00:13:08,740
The sponginess of muscles and flesh can be experienced as elasticity, cohesiveness.

119
00:13:09,500 --> 00:13:13,345
The feeling of movement caused by breathing can also be isolated.

120
00:13:14,320 --> 00:13:15,120
Why do this?

121
00:13:16,001 --> 00:13:18,405
Simply to break down the concept of wholeness.

122
00:13:18,986 --> 00:13:24,355
For with the concept of wholeness comes the concept of substance, real independent existence.

123
00:13:25,096 --> 00:13:26,298
The me, the I.

124
00:13:27,759 --> 00:13:30,243
Such as, I feel, therefore I am.

125
00:13:30,302 --> 00:13:32,186
I think, therefore I am.

126
00:13:32,626 --> 00:13:35,811
And of course, I suffer, therefore I am.

127
00:13:36,712 --> 00:13:37,594
And that's the delusions.

128
00:13:39,278 --> 00:13:42,643
Then there are all the perceptions that the mind produces every moment.

129
00:13:43,344 --> 00:13:45,206
This is the second aggregate, sanya.

130
00:13:46,629 --> 00:13:49,812
From this basic contact we get our perceptions of taste.

131
00:13:50,754 --> 00:14:05,556
Whether something is salty, sweet, bitter, astringent or sour, that's why I like to stress the importance of eating, because we get in touch with this ever-present flow of perceptions and we can begin to see how they build up into the concept of a particular dish.

132
00:14:07,105 --> 00:14:11,109
If we were blindfolded, we'd still be able to tell it was spaghetti and not curry.

133
00:14:12,409 --> 00:14:23,581
But when we eat mindfully, we become aware of the different tastes that go into making up the supposed one taste, such as the hardness of spaghetti, the sweetness and saltiness in the sauce, and so on.

134
00:14:24,523 --> 00:14:29,106
It again breaks up for us the delusion that there's only one taste in the taste of spaghetti.

135
00:14:31,750 --> 00:14:34,513
Then there's feeling, the third aggregate, vedana.

136
00:14:35,033 --> 00:14:38,817
What is meant here is the secondary response to sensations.

137
00:14:39,898 --> 00:14:45,965
Feelings arise when we experience all these perceptions as likeable or unlikable, pleasant or unpleasant.

138
00:14:47,505 --> 00:14:51,610
This also includes how we experience the feelings in our body caused by emotions.

139
00:14:52,912 --> 00:15:00,179
Again, when we concentrate inwardly, we can see that we divide our experience of life into pleasant and unpleasant.

140
00:15:01,375 --> 00:15:09,464
Although we also talk about neutral feelings, if we get close up to them, we will discover some delicate shade of liking or disliking there.

141
00:15:10,745 --> 00:15:19,134
These three khanda, aggregates, are the materials upon which the fourth khanda works, the sankhara, the volitional formations.

142
00:15:20,615 --> 00:15:23,479
It's here that self steps in and tries to take control.

143
00:15:24,600 --> 00:15:28,664
A world is created out of all the percepts, perceptions and feelings.

144
00:15:28,847 --> 00:15:32,052
Our whole emotional and intellectual life springs out of this.

145
00:15:33,293 --> 00:15:37,019
And it's all manufactured by self for the pleasure of self, when we're deluded.

146
00:15:37,899 --> 00:15:43,347
And the creator is our will, which empowers all the intentions we make throughout our life.

147
00:15:45,009 --> 00:15:51,379
It's with these sankara, volitional formations, fabrications, creations, that we go out and do things.

148
00:15:52,253 --> 00:15:59,645
For the enlightened person, of course, it becomes a way of expressing wisdom into the world by way of compassionate action and service.

149
00:16:01,710 --> 00:16:04,615
And finally there are the acts of cognition, vijnana.

150
00:16:05,355 --> 00:16:07,220
This is a discriminative consciousness.

151
00:16:08,240 --> 00:16:13,029
It sees everything as separate, whether it be by way of contradiction or comparison.

152
00:16:13,886 --> 00:16:18,474
Vijnana is the mind's ability to hold a frame up that is then understood.

153
00:16:19,475 --> 00:16:26,746
It's like a mirror which holds all the images together as a whole and gives us the impression that we live in a solid world.

154
00:16:28,470 --> 00:16:34,219
We simply couldn't function if all we were aware of was the storm of perceptions coming through the sense doors.

155
00:16:35,441 --> 00:16:41,110
It is the primary knowing, it is the faculty that tells us there's a bell ringing and it's lunchtime.

156
00:16:42,236 --> 00:16:47,224
It's not to be confused with the understanding or the intuitive intelligence, satipanya.

157
00:16:48,125 --> 00:16:50,388
That, as we shall see, is something else.

158
00:16:52,610 --> 00:17:11,636
So this is one way the Buddha deconstructs our experience of the world by way of the khandha, the aggregates of form or matter, basic perceptions, feelings in the body caused both by the body itself and the mind, volitional formations which are all our emotional and thought life,

159
00:17:11,903 --> 00:17:17,170
manufactured by our power of will, and finally cognition or a primary knowing.

160
00:17:18,551 --> 00:17:20,074
And we can use this in our practice.

161
00:17:20,614 --> 00:17:22,817
We can simply note things from this point of view.

162
00:17:23,538 --> 00:17:37,496
We note movement in the breath, heat or cold, a fire element, pressure, the earth element or the tightness we feel, the air element, the sheer movement, the lightness of joy, the warmth of love, and so on.

163
00:17:38,557 --> 00:17:41,421
Perceptions we note as images or thoughts.

164
00:17:41,704 --> 00:17:45,691
Feelings we feel directly, experience intimately and note.

165
00:17:46,852 --> 00:17:56,066
The sankhara are all our intentions that manufacture the fantasies and thoughts, both consciously volitional or habitual, throughout the whole day.

166
00:17:56,086 --> 00:18:04,438
And cognition can be recognized in the act of noting of any object, no matter what it is, as the object we come to note.

167
00:18:06,763 --> 00:18:12,633
The second way the Buddha deconstructs the human experience is by way of the avenues or spheres of cognition.

168
00:18:13,934 --> 00:18:17,760
Each avenue or sphere being distinct, exclusive and discrete.

169
00:18:18,742 --> 00:18:20,525
The five senses and the mind itself.

170
00:18:21,666 --> 00:18:24,791
When it comes to the five senses, we can't mix them.

171
00:18:25,653 --> 00:18:29,599
We can't smell with our eyes and we can't see with our ears and so on.

172
00:18:30,300 --> 00:18:34,948
They are quite different avenues of consciousness or spheres of experience

173
00:18:35,266 --> 00:18:38,130
and this is what the Buddha calls them, the āyātana, the spheres.

174
00:18:39,611 --> 00:18:46,619
The mind itself is seen as the sixth sense in this case, for it makes sense of all the other incoming data.

175
00:18:48,281 --> 00:18:50,805
What is actually received into the mind is quite minimal.

176
00:18:51,726 --> 00:18:53,969
The mind has to work hard to put it all together.

177
00:18:54,950 --> 00:19:00,497
But it is quite discreet from the sense-bases, for if all the five senses were to disappear,

178
00:19:00,730 --> 00:19:07,661
The mind would have nothing to do but mess around in the library of its own images, thoughts, moods and emotions.

179
00:19:10,286 --> 00:19:13,991
Now when we experience an event, it is experienced again as a whole.

180
00:19:14,972 --> 00:19:19,460
At the cinema or watching a video or TV, it's all one experience.

181
00:19:20,281 --> 00:19:25,269
We see the film, hear the dialogue, the music, we taste the popcorn or biscuits.

182
00:19:25,289 --> 00:19:27,192
It's all one big experience.

183
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:33,987
It's only when we start concentrating on the moment that we realize there are a myriad of mental processes going on.

184
00:19:34,847 --> 00:19:38,172
In fact, there can only arise one act of cognition at a time.

185
00:19:39,933 --> 00:19:56,994
The mind can only perceive one piece of data at any one given moment, but it's all going so fast and cognition is so good at manufacturing pictures out of that data that we experience life as one continuous whole, not as a series of discrete perceptions.

186
00:19:58,425 --> 00:20:05,354
Can you imagine watching TV, where at one moment you see the picture, that goes out, and then you hear the dialogue?

187
00:20:06,234 --> 00:20:11,020
You put a biscuit in your mouth, and on the taste you lose both the vision and the hearing of the program.

188
00:20:12,541 --> 00:20:16,567
It would be impossible to live like that in a sort of stroboscopic universe.

189
00:20:17,929 --> 00:20:22,253
Thanks to the speed of cognition, it's all magically formulated into one piece.

190
00:20:23,214 --> 00:20:27,640
But there lies our delusion, because we believe that's the way things really are.

191
00:20:28,462 --> 00:20:36,532
The point of insight meditation is to see beyond the apparent and to see that everything is only a compendium, a collection.

192
00:20:37,694 --> 00:20:40,699
There's nothing real or solid about any experience whatsoever.

193
00:20:41,420 --> 00:20:44,163
As the Buddha says, it's all like bubbles in a stream.

194
00:20:45,545 --> 00:20:50,791
By noting our meditative experiences along these lines, the avenues of consciousness,

195
00:20:51,176 --> 00:20:59,726
and realizing how discreet they are, we get in touch with how we fabricate the world and undermine the delusion of wholeness or substance.

196
00:21:00,907 --> 00:21:04,592
And this, of course, rebounds upon the concept of the self, of the me.

197
00:21:05,593 --> 00:21:06,313
What is this me?

198
00:21:06,814 --> 00:21:14,281
Where is this me to be found if everything I believe to be me is nothing but a collection of sensual and mental data?

199
00:21:16,387 --> 00:21:21,836
Now there is another way the Buddha deconstructs our experience by way of the elements, the dhatu.

200
00:21:23,317 --> 00:21:27,804
I want to mention it briefly here because it tells us how far this deconstruction can go.

201
00:21:27,844 --> 00:21:34,413
The last two of the 24 elements are called the mind object and the mind cognition elements.

202
00:21:35,734 --> 00:21:41,383
These go into a moment to moment detail of how the mind manufactures a single thought.

203
00:21:41,566 --> 00:21:44,548
And believe it or not, this can actually be experienced.

204
00:21:45,288 --> 00:21:54,478
That's how profound this meditation can take us into seeing how the mind works to generate a world and ultimately how we come to be deceived by it.

205
00:21:56,700 --> 00:22:03,806
Now apart from this process of deconstruction, there is another way in which we can see that the self is a false identity.

206
00:22:04,906 --> 00:22:10,392
The self likes to think of itself in control, the agent, to have power over.

207
00:22:11,214 --> 00:22:15,262
It wants to do my own thing, in my own way, in my own time.

208
00:22:16,405 --> 00:22:20,233
The Buddha, after he became enlightened, sought out his five companions.

209
00:22:21,155 --> 00:22:22,979
He found them in Isipatana Park.

210
00:22:24,142 --> 00:22:31,958
There, he first talked about the Four Noble Truths, and one of the company attained the first level of enlightenment.

211
00:22:32,224 --> 00:22:33,606
stream entry, Sotapanna.

212
00:22:34,387 --> 00:22:37,352
But when he gave his second discourse, they were all fully awakened.

213
00:22:38,193 --> 00:22:42,420
This discourse is called the discourse on the characteristic of not-self.

214
00:22:43,882 --> 00:22:44,702
Here's the gist of it.

215
00:22:45,463 --> 00:22:50,151
Meditators, the body, form, the sense bases, are not-self.

216
00:22:51,251 --> 00:22:54,217
If the body was a self, it would not lead to suffering.

217
00:22:54,656 --> 00:23:00,105
For one could say to the body, let the body be healthy, let the body not be sick.

218
00:23:00,388 --> 00:23:01,569
But the body isn't like that.

219
00:23:02,451 --> 00:23:06,434
It is because we can't tell the body what to do that suffering arises.

220
00:23:08,938 --> 00:23:11,119
We feel we have control over the body, don't we?

221
00:23:12,020 --> 00:23:15,144
I mean, we can make it walk and talk and eat and so on.

222
00:23:16,085 --> 00:23:20,849
But this is like the driver of a car who can make the car start and stop, turn left or right.

223
00:23:21,891 --> 00:23:24,933
But what control has the driver over the car in itself?

224
00:23:26,234 --> 00:23:28,978
And how much does a driver know about the workings of a car?

225
00:23:30,156 --> 00:23:32,421
we find ourselves in a similar position with the body.

226
00:23:33,624 --> 00:23:39,535
On closer inspection, we experience little of the internal workings, never mind know about them.

227
00:23:40,395 --> 00:23:43,342
Indeed, the body, for the most part, takes care of itself.

228
00:23:45,405 --> 00:23:47,710
What do I experience of the digestive system?

229
00:23:48,771 --> 00:23:50,355
What control have I got over it?

230
00:23:51,196 --> 00:23:52,839
What about the circulatory system?

231
00:23:54,170 --> 00:23:57,915
I haven't a clue in terms of real experience what my blood is doing.

232
00:23:58,817 --> 00:24:05,107
I've read about it, but I've never experienced hemoglobin turning red when it meets with oxygen in the lungs.

233
00:24:06,509 --> 00:24:13,781
I feel my abdomen and chest moving when I breathe, but I've never experienced the blood exchanging carbon dioxide for oxygen.

234
00:24:14,605 --> 00:24:17,690
The whole thing just works altogether without me interfering.

235
00:24:18,751 --> 00:24:30,071
In fact, it's when I don't recognise that I'm not the body that I'm in danger of doing it harm, when I push the body too hard or overeat and drink intoxicants and so on.

236
00:24:31,875 --> 00:24:37,305
In other words, although we have a certain amount of control over the body, it's quite superficial.

237
00:24:38,163 --> 00:24:41,688
I can make it walk and talk but I can't make it grow one way or the other.

238
00:24:42,409 --> 00:24:43,289
Or make it beautiful.

239
00:24:44,171 --> 00:24:46,594
I can't will myself to become a great athlete.

240
00:24:47,315 --> 00:24:50,019
I can't stop it growing old and I can't stop it dying.

241
00:24:50,799 --> 00:24:52,982
My control over the body is superficial.

242
00:24:53,903 --> 00:24:58,470
And yet I'm utterly dependent on this body for my existence on this planet.

243
00:24:59,511 --> 00:25:00,373
A humbling thought.

244
00:25:03,121 --> 00:25:12,314
In the same way, we can go through the other khandha, the aggregates, and see that it's the same with the perceptions we have, the feelings, the emotions, and the thoughts we have.

245
00:25:13,536 --> 00:25:17,781
Eventually, we have very little control over the type of personality we have.

246
00:25:18,844 --> 00:25:24,132
Even when we become fully enlightened, we don't change the flavor of our personality radically.

247
00:25:25,232 --> 00:25:28,538
The Buddha was still recognizably Siddhartha Gautama.

248
00:25:28,805 --> 00:25:34,875
His five companions recognized him as such, but that personality was then purified of all malevolence.

249
00:25:36,699 --> 00:25:40,125
This lack of power can be seen even in the way we perceive the world.

250
00:25:40,747 --> 00:25:48,039
Humans can see only a particular band within the whole spectrum of color, and each of us has our own experience of color.

251
00:25:48,842 --> 00:25:51,707
Some of us are colorblind, some of us have poor sight.

252
00:25:52,817 --> 00:25:56,102
Our emotional life is also conditioned, and our thought life too.

253
00:25:57,022 --> 00:26:00,767
For instance, certain types of music will affect us, other types won't.

254
00:26:01,929 --> 00:26:05,752
Our thought is bound up with the language we speak and the culture that's produced it.

255
00:26:06,835 --> 00:26:11,559
European people, for instance, have very different cultural values to people in the East.

256
00:26:11,579 --> 00:26:16,246
With insight, of course, we do begin to create a better interior life.

257
00:26:16,266 --> 00:26:19,990
But it will still be greatly conditioned by our culture and environment.

258
00:26:22,365 --> 00:26:26,642
We've now discussed two aspects of how the Buddha undermines the self-delusion.

259
00:26:27,625 --> 00:26:33,507
By deconstructing a seeming whole and by questioning the power that self presumes to have.

260
00:26:34,111 --> 00:26:41,558
In this way, the Buddha tries to undermine the belief that the body and mind are some sort of eternal person, soul or spirit.

261
00:26:42,599 --> 00:26:45,442
But our delusion doesn't stop there at the obvious, so to speak.

262
00:26:46,042 --> 00:26:57,816
He also wanted to undermine the belief that beneath these attributes, the body and mind as we experience them, lies any other real self whatsoever, something which is eternal.

263
00:26:59,237 --> 00:27:00,498
Take a hand, for instance.

264
00:27:01,538 --> 00:27:03,020
Let's look at it and feel it.

265
00:27:04,012 --> 00:27:07,558
We see it has certain colour, a certain shape.

266
00:27:07,578 --> 00:27:10,263
We feel it has soft parts and hard parts, and so on.

267
00:27:11,526 --> 00:27:15,053
Let's presume that we've seen and felt a hand to an ultimate degree.

268
00:27:15,814 --> 00:27:16,996
We know all its attributes.

269
00:27:17,958 --> 00:27:20,021
We realise it's made up of bits and pieces.

270
00:27:21,364 --> 00:27:23,367
But let's say this isn't the real hand.

271
00:27:24,048 --> 00:27:28,636
To discover the real hand, we must, as it were, slip these attributes away.

272
00:27:29,596 --> 00:27:39,490
Can you imagine taking off your hand as you would a glove to reveal another hand which was real, substantial, unchangeable, eternal, indestructible, and so on?

273
00:27:40,671 --> 00:27:43,895
It was this sort of idea that the Buddha also wanted to undermine.

274
00:27:44,977 --> 00:27:52,126
For this was the more subtle meaning of the word atta, self, in his time, as it is today for people who believe in an afterlife.

275
00:27:52,883 --> 00:28:00,810
namely that there is a subtle body beneath or within the material body that is substantial, immortal, and will go on to live forever.

276
00:28:02,571 --> 00:28:19,228
At the time of the Buddha, the scriptures of the Brahmins, now called Hinduism, had been developing along similar lines, but in the general understanding of things, the Atta, the Self, had come to mean both the empirical Self and the Eternal Self, the capital S.

277
00:28:20,811 --> 00:28:29,746
The empirical self is how we experience ourselves now as personalities, as persons with thoughts, emotions, sensations, relationships and so on.

278
00:28:30,748 --> 00:28:39,141
But the eternal self posited some self beneath or transcendent of this, like the real hand beneath the apparent hand.

279
00:28:40,201 --> 00:28:44,808
Whatever later Hinduism came to believe, it was all confusion in the Buddha's time.

280
00:28:45,611 --> 00:28:55,648
So the Buddha simply swept that confusion aside by telling everyone that anything they conceived of, an eternal soul, spirit or self, was but wishful thinking.

281
00:28:56,810 --> 00:29:03,221
Put another way, anything they experienced by way of the body, heart and mind was not self, anatta.

282
00:29:04,635 --> 00:29:16,731
Whether physical, psychological or ethereal, whatever self a person experienced themselves to be, that self was a construct and had no real, substantial or essential existence.

283
00:29:19,415 --> 00:29:25,423
Now let us remember that the Buddha is concerned to get us to experience this, to come to know this for ourselves.

284
00:29:26,325 --> 00:29:30,069
We have to have practical, direct, personal experience.

285
00:29:31,163 --> 00:29:37,291
Remember, to be convinced of all this by way of thought, by way of a philosophical proposition, just won't do.

286
00:29:38,473 --> 00:29:43,922
We might be able to write deep philosophical books about it, but that won't bring us to the end of suffering.

287
00:29:45,324 --> 00:29:57,863
So the Buddha now deconstructs the human being, this psychophysical organism, into yet another division in order to lead us to an experiential understanding, a direct realization of not-self.

288
00:29:59,377 --> 00:30:06,210
He now teaches us to look at ourselves from the point of view of the four foundations of mindfulness, the satipatthana.

289
00:30:07,270 --> 00:30:24,339
They can be seen as four frames of reference, whereby we can experience this psychophysical organism I call me, break down its illusion of wholeness, and discover indeed that there is no other reality beneath them, within them, above them, or anywhere around them.

290
00:30:25,602 --> 00:30:30,728
You will by now be familiar with all the terminology but it's looked at in a slightly different way.

291
00:30:31,769 --> 00:30:39,678
This is important because up till now we've looked at ways of deconstructing the human being but they've had an intellectual bias.

292
00:30:40,700 --> 00:30:44,124
With the Satipatthana the Buddha is being immediate and practical.

293
00:30:45,105 --> 00:30:54,816
This is the way we can note, observe, feel and experience and so come to understand the way we really are by the direct path of Vipassanā.

294
00:30:55,893 --> 00:30:59,416
The first is Kayanupasana, investigating the body.

295
00:31:00,898 --> 00:31:08,287
It means we need to be mindful of all our daily actions, standing, walking and so on, and to see that no action is one thing.

296
00:31:08,346 --> 00:31:10,910
It's made up of a myriad of movements.

297
00:31:11,730 --> 00:31:13,613
This includes the action of breathing.

298
00:31:14,855 --> 00:31:18,759
At its most profound level is to see how the mind contacts the body.

299
00:31:19,941 --> 00:31:25,426
That's when we experience those four great elements of earth, fire and so on we discussed earlier.

300
00:31:26,420 --> 00:31:28,564
Then there's a whole area of feeling in the body.

301
00:31:28,984 --> 00:31:30,347
That's vedanupasana.

302
00:31:31,349 --> 00:31:37,582
These feelings, remember, can be caused by the body, as when our knees hurt, or by the mind, as when an emotion comes up.

303
00:31:38,624 --> 00:31:39,885
Then there's cittanupasana.

304
00:31:40,647 --> 00:31:47,601
Here we note, feel, observe, and come to know our states of mind, all the moods and emotions, thoughts and images.

305
00:31:48,069 --> 00:31:51,353
whether it's concentrated or not, suffering or not, and so on.

306
00:31:52,575 --> 00:31:54,395
And finally, there's Dhammanupassana.

307
00:31:55,217 --> 00:31:59,701
This refers to certain teachings which are specific to the Buddha Dhamma.

308
00:31:59,721 --> 00:32:15,478
The five aggregates, the five hindrances, the six sense spheres, the seven factors of enlightenment, and the four noble truths, which include, of course, the three characteristics of existence, impermanence, unsatisfactoriness, and not-self.

309
00:32:17,263 --> 00:32:20,228
We have, of course, touched upon all these during the last few days.

310
00:32:21,469 --> 00:32:35,365
These satipatthana, establishments of awareness, are the frames of reference by which the intuitive wisdom, paññā, can investigate and come to see, to realize the human condition from an enlightened point of view.

311
00:32:38,209 --> 00:32:45,718
In meditation, through the process of vipassana, we can begin to experience directly this doctrine of anatta, not self.

312
00:32:46,390 --> 00:32:48,935
The most obvious way is through the noting technique.

313
00:32:49,959 --> 00:32:57,817
Whenever something comes into our attention, be it the breath, a sensation, a feeling, a thought, we mentally point to it as it were.

314
00:32:58,877 --> 00:32:59,519
We note it.

315
00:33:00,078 --> 00:33:05,085
We say, rising, falling, itching, anger, joy, and so on.

316
00:33:06,046 --> 00:33:08,588
This pointing at it distances us from it.

317
00:33:09,430 --> 00:33:14,635
What we are really saying is, there are the feelings of the breath, rising and falling.

318
00:33:15,135 --> 00:33:17,499
There are the feelings of itching, and so on.

319
00:33:18,039 --> 00:33:20,903
There, over there, not here.

320
00:33:21,777 --> 00:33:41,237
not here within the knowing we are objectifying the inner world in the same way as babies and toddlers we began to objectify the outer world by pointing at the inner objects the sensations feelings thoughts we're distancing ourselves from them and the noting technique helps us to do that

321
00:33:41,722 --> 00:33:53,601
As our meditation deepens, then thought disappears, the noting stops, and we learn to perceive that what we experience within ourselves is not the same as the knowing which is experiencing it.

322
00:33:54,682 --> 00:33:57,988
At this point, the true nature of the knowing begins to dawn upon us.

323
00:33:58,468 --> 00:33:59,670
What is this awareness?

324
00:34:00,711 --> 00:34:03,276
What is this intuitive intelligence?

325
00:34:03,296 --> 00:34:04,577
What is satipanya?

326
00:34:05,398 --> 00:34:10,666
Now that's the question, and this meditation is leading us directly to that answer.

327
00:34:12,233 --> 00:34:13,434
Now here's the paradox.

328
00:34:14,135 --> 00:34:20,887
Why is it that the Buddha says that nibbana is just as we would want any eternal self to be, but it is not self?

329
00:34:22,291 --> 00:34:28,621
Unlike everything in the phenomenal world, which is anicca, transient, nibbana is nicca, not transient.

330
00:34:29,175 --> 00:34:30,898
It doesn't arise and pass away.

331
00:34:30,938 --> 00:34:35,467
It is the deathless, immortal, just like an eternal self.

332
00:34:36,748 --> 00:34:46,706
Unlike the enlightened state where everything is eventually unsatisfactory, Nibbana is a state of complete contentment, perfect peace, yet it is not an eternal self.

333
00:34:48,208 --> 00:34:52,516
This is expressed most clearly in the three verses we chant every morning.

334
00:34:52,987 --> 00:34:55,469
All conditioned things are impermanent.

335
00:34:55,489 --> 00:34:57,693
All conditioned things are unsatisfactory.

336
00:34:57,972 --> 00:35:02,298
But all conditioned things and the unconditioned are not self.

337
00:35:03,199 --> 00:35:08,666
When this is perceived with wisdom, one becomes disenchanted with what cannot satisfy.

338
00:35:09,668 --> 00:35:11,951
Just this is the path of purification.

339
00:35:13,552 --> 00:35:20,681
When we think about it, is there ever a time when the idea of me doesn't come up without a self-awareness?

340
00:35:21,978 --> 00:35:23,960
Indeed, isn't that what we mean by a self?

341
00:35:24,481 --> 00:35:25,702
The feeling of a me.

342
00:35:27,824 --> 00:35:29,427
Is there a self in deep sleep?

343
00:35:30,869 --> 00:35:31,990
We just presume it, don't we?

344
00:35:33,753 --> 00:35:41,762
I presume that since I went to sleep feeling myself to be me, and wake up feeling the same, my self must have been there all through sleep.

345
00:35:42,885 --> 00:35:44,065
But it's an inference, isn't it?

346
00:35:44,686 --> 00:35:45,228
An assumption.

347
00:35:46,208 --> 00:35:47,030
How can we prove it?

348
00:35:48,711 --> 00:35:51,815
In meditation we feel ourselves to be an observer.

349
00:35:52,235 --> 00:35:56,121
There seems always to be somebody watching, doing, experiencing.

350
00:35:57,163 --> 00:36:00,327
In pure vipassana, this feeling vanishes entirely.

351
00:36:01,130 --> 00:36:07,119
Yet there is still the watching, the doing, the experiencing, but no sense of a self doing it.

352
00:36:08,340 --> 00:36:11,847
That's why the Buddha says, In the seeing, there's only the seeing.

353
00:36:12,427 --> 00:36:14,050
In the hearing, there's only the hearing.

354
00:36:14,692 --> 00:36:17,195
In the cognizing, there's only the cognizing.

355
00:36:19,302 --> 00:36:24,367
Can we, unenlightened beings as we are, get a taste of what that selfless state might be?

356
00:36:25,670 --> 00:36:28,313
Yes, indeed we can, but again a paradox.

357
00:36:29,074 --> 00:36:31,336
We can't do it by an act of self-will.

358
00:36:32,318 --> 00:36:35,081
It's not within the power of self to go beyond self.

359
00:36:36,023 --> 00:36:41,208
All we can do is set up the conditions whereby we might have a not-self experience.

360
00:36:42,291 --> 00:36:45,715
And here is where the Buddha shows the depth of his gift as a teacher.

361
00:36:46,268 --> 00:36:57,028
He asks us only to be concerned with establishing right awareness, not to bother about experiencing nibbana or not-self, which we simply can't achieve by an act of will.

362
00:36:58,411 --> 00:37:00,396
So what is right awareness?

363
00:37:02,434 --> 00:37:05,119
First of all, it's not intellectual knowledge.

364
00:37:06,302 --> 00:37:12,552
If everything said in this talk has been fairly new, you may very well be confused by the five of these and the four of those.

365
00:37:12,853 --> 00:37:13,494
Well, don't worry.

366
00:37:14,556 --> 00:37:18,443
If you're interested in it at all, then after this course you can read and study it all.

367
00:37:18,682 --> 00:37:22,028
But here in meditation, it's not even necessary to know it.

368
00:37:22,949 --> 00:37:24,492
So I go on about it.

369
00:37:24,742 --> 00:37:29,891
because through these arguments we can at least become intellectually convinced of our insubstantiality.

370
00:37:30,711 --> 00:37:36,880
Being convinced intellectually, hopefully we have more faith in vipassana and more eagerness to see if it's really true.

371
00:37:37,461 --> 00:37:40,106
In other words, it's about getting a right attitude.

372
00:37:41,869 --> 00:37:43,150
Now, presumably we have it now.

373
00:37:44,032 --> 00:37:49,940
So we can concentrate just on the practice, which is simply to be aware of all that arises and passes away.

374
00:37:51,574 --> 00:38:15,304
As we begin to centre in on what we are experiencing, let's say the sensations caused by the breath, using the noting to keep the thinking mind from making us lose our focus, sati, awareness begins to concentrate on, gather around a smaller and smaller event, a smaller and smaller unit of time, drawing itself into the immediate present moment.

375
00:38:16,280 --> 00:38:21,105
And at that point there is no time to think, no time to reflect.

376
00:38:22,065 --> 00:38:25,309
The thinking mind has no time in which to think.

377
00:38:25,831 --> 00:38:26,931
The noting stops.

378
00:38:28,193 --> 00:38:37,422
As the interval of time decreases, so the time interval is so small we can experience single sensations arising and passing away.

379
00:38:38,485 --> 00:38:44,210
This sati awareness doesn't even have the time to recognize its own presence.

380
00:38:44,748 --> 00:38:48,733
seeing itself, feeling itself mirrored within the mind like a shadow.

381
00:38:49,295 --> 00:38:50,777
It constructs an image of itself.

382
00:38:51,699 --> 00:38:54,885
That image we experience as self-awareness.

383
00:38:55,626 --> 00:39:02,336
But as this awareness sits simply in the presenting instant, even that feeling of self-awareness disappears.

384
00:39:03,217 --> 00:39:07,465
And there is the experience of just observing, just watching.

385
00:39:07,867 --> 00:39:13,717
the feeling, the idea, the belief that there is a soul, a self, a spirit, disappears.

386
00:39:14,458 --> 00:39:25,538
For that moment, and for longer periods of time, if the practice is good, the meditator experiences pure awareness, unadulterated by the view or feeling of a self.

387
00:39:26,699 --> 00:39:36,690
We can see now that the Anatta teaching is not saying there is nothing, but that whatever ultimate reality is, it is not a self or a feeling of a self.

388
00:39:37,469 --> 00:39:42,094
In ultimate reality, just as in the phenomenal world, there are no things.

389
00:39:42,835 --> 00:39:53,246
And the feeling of self-awareness is the feeling of a thing, but the subtlest of things, and therefore the most difficult of things to perceive as insubstantial and not self.

390
00:39:54,829 --> 00:39:56,492
So how do we get a glimpse of this?

391
00:39:57,614 --> 00:40:00,358
By doing the practice according to the Buddha's instructions.

392
00:40:00,960 --> 00:40:02,181
Forget about nibbana.

393
00:40:02,523 --> 00:40:06,148
Forget about trying to have a spiritual experience.

394
00:40:06,168 --> 00:40:08,271
Forget about the vipassana insights.

395
00:40:08,893 --> 00:40:10,376
Forget about achieving anything.

396
00:40:10,956 --> 00:40:13,581
Save a moment-to-moment attentiveness.

397
00:40:14,016 --> 00:40:21,447
Just place all our energy into observing the presenting object, be it a sensation, emotion or thought.

398
00:40:22,327 --> 00:40:26,672
Ultimate truth is to be experienced in the presenting event, the here and now.

399
00:40:27,353 --> 00:40:31,079
Hence, our whole effort is simply to be present.

400
00:40:31,760 --> 00:40:33,983
Ultimately, we will have that glimpse.

401
00:40:37,253 --> 00:40:46,123
The Buddha says there is a consciousness which has no characteristics, no attributes, beyond the realm of scientific measurement.

402
00:40:47,065 --> 00:40:53,454
A consciousness that is without boundary, in all directions, lustrous, full of light, awake.

403
00:40:54,394 --> 00:40:56,237
Just this is the end of suffering.

404
00:40:58,760 --> 00:41:00,121
Let's pause here for a moment.

405
00:43:01,027 --> 00:43:03,875
Whenever we look at something, that becomes an object.

406
00:43:04,876 --> 00:43:06,661
Being an object, it cannot be the subject.

407
00:43:07,744 --> 00:43:09,949
The knowing cannot be what it knows.

408
00:43:11,172 --> 00:43:16,065
Even the feeling of a self, when we are self-aware, self-conscious, must also be an object.

409
00:43:16,827 --> 00:43:18,530
It cannot be that which knows.

410
00:43:19,657 --> 00:43:23,061
Grasping this, at first a fear and anxiety may arise in us.

411
00:43:23,882 --> 00:43:28,708
Who are we if we're not this body, these emotions, these thoughts, this personality?

412
00:43:29,769 --> 00:43:38,780
But when we begin to see things as they really are, and where our true nature actually resides, then a real peace, a real happiness begins to flower.

413
00:43:39,802 --> 00:43:42,324
And where does our true nature reside?

414
00:43:42,304 --> 00:43:57,525
It resides in our ability to discover a relationship to the world without and the world within, wherein we find intimacy without identity, where we are utterly engaged, utterly involved and yet detached.

415
00:43:58,586 --> 00:44:02,771
Such paradox can only be solved by that knowing the Buddha within.

416
00:44:05,175 --> 00:44:06,396
So we have to keep working at it.

417
00:44:06,918 --> 00:44:09,561
Tomorrow is the seventh day of our endeavour.

418
00:44:09,693 --> 00:44:14,059
We're now accustomed to the routine, so we can begin to raise the effort even further.

419
00:44:14,900 --> 00:44:18,065
Now don't forget, we're not trying to get anything, achieve anything.

420
00:44:18,686 --> 00:44:26,958
We're not trying to succeed at anything, but a constant awareness of anything that arises and passes away within the focus of our attention.

421
00:44:27,659 --> 00:44:29,300
That's our sole job.

422
00:44:29,822 --> 00:44:30,822
That's all there is to it.

423
00:44:31,423 --> 00:44:35,009
To be aware of what is happening right here, right now.

424
00:44:35,028 --> 00:44:36,291
That's it.

425
00:44:37,722 --> 00:44:42,530
A final word from the Buddha, coming from a collection known as the Udana, the inspired verses.

426
00:44:44,092 --> 00:44:59,898
Whose attentiveness stands like a mountain, steady, unperturbed, unattached to whatever tempts indulgence, unangered by whatever tempts aversion, when there is such imperturbable composure, how can suffering arise?

427
00:45:02,224 --> 00:45:12,184
Now that you are no longer fooled by the dictates of self, without doubt your unflagging devotion to the practice of moment-to-moment awareness will bear great fruit.

428
00:45:13,947 --> 00:45:23,726
May you achieve full liberation from the delusion of self and attain to that state of perfect serenity sooner rather than later.
